        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The goal of this proposal is to image the narrow rings around the HD141569 disc. The diameter of the rings along the major axis is approx 7arcseconds but in any given direction the largest scale of the emission does not exceed 5''. We have also checked that our ALMA simulations with single pointing and 0.4'' resolution recover the flux from the disc model efficiently. And this is mainly thanks to the flux being contained in these narrow features.
For the CO line (even if it may be extended over the disc) this is achieved kinematically, because we know that in each spectral channel the structure of the emission does not exceed the 5''limit. So we have thoroughly ensured that we do not suffer from filtering and 5'' is our largest spatial scale.

Chosen 0.4'' resolution is enough to resolve the gap between the rings, as seen in scattered light (proposal Fig 2) and recover all the narrow features of interest. 1.7km/s will resolve the CO 3-2 line (Dent+2005) observed with FWHM of 8km/s. 

The time request is based on the S/N of 5 and more that we wish to achieve in the continuum imaging. The continuum flux in the outer belt is &gt;100uJy and so we aim at 20uJy rms levels. With the proposed setup this can be achieved in 4.44h total time, of which 2.01h on-source. As discussed above, single pointing is sufficient. Simultaneously, we will detect and image the line of estimated flux 0.5Jy/beam.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
