    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The disc around HD141569 presents a unique opportunity to investigate the crossover from a gas-dominated protoplanetary disc phase and dust dominated debris disc phase. CO and PAH emission point to presence of gas and small dust in the system, while the low excess SED indicates an optically thin dust disc. Its architecture, with gap and spirals possibly caused by a large separation planet, and the age of 5Myr all suggest this disc is a missing link between old gas-rich discs and young debris discs. We propose that during this transformation the debris disc is born encapsulated in the remnant primordial gas. Our proposed imaging of gas and dust in the disc will reveal whether the largest dust and planetesimals are strongly confined to the observed narrow spirals tightly wound around the gap, confirming the debris-like dynamics. A comparison with the gas imaging will similarly offer an insight in the gas to dust distribution at this critical moment of disc evolution. Considering that very little is known about the transition to debris phase, the proposed observations will, rather than testing theories, lay the foundations for constructing new ones.</prp:abstract>
